text: Yeah, so that's, again, a great question. And the way we do it is that it's not really 50-50. And the way I think I've been talking about it, it may sound like we give equal weights to the model and to our own judgment. And we really don't. Our models are, I think, well thought out, consistent, based on long-term relationships. All that stuff is hugely important. And the model, in a lot of cases, you can think about it as getting more weight. What we do from a qualitative perspective, sort of building a quote-unquote quantum mental type strategy, is, again, trying to poke holes in the model. It's what is it missing? And if we can't come up with good rationale for what it's missing, then we'll usually just do what the model, what we built the model to do. We'll usually follow those traits. But in cases where, again, that whole long Brazil short coffee trade, that's one that you just... Just look at it and you're like, wait, that's just a weird trade. I don't understand that trade. And that doesn't mean you kill it. That means you learn more about it. You try to dig in and say, okay, why would you want to do this trade? I'm a big believer of if you don't understand a trade, don't do it. The time to learn about a trade is not after you put it on. I think sometimes people forget that. They hear about an idea and they put on the trade and then they go back later after it didn't go well. Like, wait a minute, why did I lose money? You didn't really understand what you were doing. You didn't really understand what you were doing.
